reviewText: First of all, it's important to realize that it's possible for a movie to be quite funny without being worthy of 5-stars.  That's the case with this show.Why it's good:1) There are plenty of funny bits, including times when I laughed right out loud.2) The use of characters who do not have any humor contrast markedly with the one character that is entirely wacko.3) The bizarre lead character is at the same time full of childlike wonder and technical ability (though he hides his abilities well).Why it's not a 5-star show:1) OK, it's an older movie, but the special effects are still quite hokey and simple.2) The characters are fun, but the acting is only marginally good.3) The storyline is extremely predictable.Does this mean that I didn't enjoy it?  No, I enjoyed the movie quite a lot.  It is, nevertheless, a fun, fun movie - though a bit crass in parts.3 stars.
summary: An incredibly silly show...not really good, but silly!

reviewText: There are some movies you could show the most humourless person on earth and if they don't laugh at it then they're beyond saving. "Rocketman" is such a film. Before I saw this movie, I never really knew that comedy could be so wacky yet so endearing and impossibly hilarious, all at the same time. The incomparable Harland Williams stars as highly eccentric computer-genius Fred Randall, who becomes the last-minute choice of a third crew member on the first mission to Mars. From before the training to the mission itself, Fred manages to turn both NASA and Mars upside down with his hilarious, but always innocent, escapades. Accompanied by his three partners - cocky commander William Overbeck, no-nonsense scientist Julie Ford and pranky chip Ulysses - Fred's adventure to Mars still leaves me in stitches. And this is coming from a man who's seen this movie many times.You won't find humour like this elsewhere, really. As Beau Bridges in the role of Bud Nesbitt rightly states, Fred is both a complete genius and a total fool. When Fred manages to keep his mouth shut (which isn't often), you might find him flying through the corridors of NASA on a runaway chair or conducting a worldwide chorus of "He's got the Whole World in his Hands". There's lots of stuff to make you gasp of breath for laughter, and I hate stupid humour - but Rocketman's humour, however wacky and often ridiculous, somehow (don't ask me how) manages to keep its integrity. There is also a lot of clever stuff for the less slapstick-loving viewers.However, the release of this DVD is another one where Disney makes the stupid decision to cut for no apparent reason. The very first scene of the movie, where Fred attempts his own 'landing' as a kid, is all-but cut, making it completely pointless and, what's worse, ruining the mirroring words of Fred as an adult. I don't understand why this cut was made, and for that, I am detracting a star from the score. However, if you want a movie that just gives you pure laughs, then this is the movie to go (even if it is a little historically incorrect).

reviewText: This show is such a wonderfully funny movie that the whole family can watch.  My family loves it!  I was laughing so hard at times that my sides ached.  It's about a man that has been dreaming of space travel since he was a little boy.  He finally has the opportunity to go with the astronaut team.  He must go through astronaut training as well as pass everything to insure that he will be able to function in space.  He's accident proned and tries to turn the attention from himself with his "It wasn't me" phrase throughout the movie.While going through space he is locked out of his oxygen chamber, whichhe is supposed to sleep in for several weeks before being awakened to complete the mission.  He does some crazy things to entertain himself until the others awaken.While on the planet he has a flatulence problem (see picture on front of DVD).  This makes for a hilarious time since his suit is attached to a fellow astronaut by a hose.Truly hilarious.  I would highly recommend watching this movie with the whole family.  I wouldn't pay the ridiculous prices that are listed here though.  I would rent it or buy the VHS version.  Disney also has it listed as a Disney Movie Rewards redemption item.  If you have bought a lot of the newer Disney DVDs, this may be the better route.

reviewText: I'm thoroughly ashamed to admit that I found this dopey movie both hilarious and oddly endearing thanks to a truly bizarre performance by Harland Williams as Fred Z. Randall a computer programmer.  (He's a cross between Pee Wee Herman and Robin Williams.)  His antics have to be seen to be believed.  The plot involves a mishap concerning a manned mission to Mars.  There's a glitch in the computer navigation system and only one man can fix it, Fred Z. Randall.  Naturally, he has to go along on the mission, with devastating results.The reason this movie works is due to the opening sequence of Fred as a boy, it's impossible not to respond to his enthusiasm, which doesn't diminish an iota as he moves into adulthood.  His enthusiasm is infectious.Yes, most of the humor could be considered lowbrow (how sophisticated can a fart joke be?); it's packed with slapstick and pratfalls.  There's nothing witty about the jokes.  Harland Williams resorts to sock puppets at one point!  It's sheer lunacy.  Depending on your point of view and your sense of humor, this will be either a hit or a complete miss.  I've watched it twice so far and each time I couldn't stop laughing.  It's hard not to like a simpleminded boob with good intentions.  "Wasn't me!"
summary: "Are we there yet?  Can I drive?"

reviewText: I remember seeing this movie when it aired on Disney channel oh so long ago, so when I saw it for $6.50 at Best Buy, I just couldn't resist.While the movie itself is still hilarious, you can easily tell that it isn't a recent movie, what with some innuendo, racial comments, and scenes that would most likely foster a rating greater than PG nowadays. The most memorable scene for most viewers will probably be the series of tests main character Fred takes to see if he's got what it takes to be part of NASA's mission to Mars. And while the humor after that sequence of scenes isn't nearly as funny, it's still a great watch overall. Then again, that could be the nostalgia talking.As for the DVD itself, it's not exactly the best. For one, you can't skip to different scenes, which is a real drag if you want to skip to certain scenes. Chapter selections are just something that even the most basic of DVDs should have, so it's strange to only see a play option on the main menu. You'll also notice if you check the back of the box that the movie was originally in widescreen, so it's another minus to have to watch the movie, knowing that it's not in the original aspect ratio.But all in all, this was a great purchase, especially since this movie practically never airs on TV now. And I'm not exactly surprised that the movie lacks a widescreen and chapter selection option, considering how cheap I got it for. Sure I would have liked them in there, but this release will do for now.

reviewText: If you rather bypass lackluster comedies along the line of Adam Sandler's "Water Boy" and Chris Farley's "Almost Heroes," then do not waste your time watching "Rocketman.""Rocketman" has comedian Harland Williams as Fred Randall who can land a NASA team on planet Mars. Randall does not appear as your typical rocket scientist. His personality resembles Dennis the Menace, always poking his nose in places he does not belong. We are expected to laugh at this misbehavior, but the tasteless humor is nothing we haven't seen before and the outcome of every incident is easily predictable. Except for one scene when clumsy Randall loses the American flag down in a canyon. He then pulls out his USA boxer shorts to mark the territory that carryover live on national television.The site of Mars looks adequate to its dull counterpart. Only sand occupies the orange planet. In contrast, it'd have been interesting had Mars inhabit alien life form shown in "Ghosts of Mars" or "Total Recall."William Sadler as commander Overbeck is more like Randall's baby sitter. Every stupid question Randall has to say gets turned down. It's not funny when a grown man imitates a child by saying, "Are we there yet?" They never get along with each other-Overbeck takes NASA seriously whereas Randall is a complete nutcase.Jessica Lundy as Julie Ford is surely adorn by male hormones. Her wholehearted blue eyes and fireball red hair unquestionably makes her the real star in this comedy, although the chimpanzee came close at second.Not a memorable comedy for adults to watch. Children should enjoy the outdated comedy because to them its humor will be fresh.

reviewText: This is a tour de force performance from a film comedian that is the funniest person this side of Jim Carrey.  Harland Williams, who you may have seen in bit parts as the Serial Killer Hitchhiker in "There's Something About Mary" and the State Trooper who takes a swig from Jim Carrey's beer bottle in "Dumb and Dumber", plays Fred Randall, an eccentric computer programmer thrust into the role of a mission specialist on a manned Mars flight.  What ensues is a laugh riot from pre-flight astronaut training to the return flight home.  The isolation room sequence and the official announcement of Randall to the Mars mission will have you in tears.  William Sadler, Jessica Lundy, and Beau Bridges costar in a film that is short on dazzling special effects, but very long on side-splitting hilarity.  For some odd reason, Disney has refused to release this film on DVD in the U.S.
summary: One of the Funniest Movies You've Never Seen

reviewText: Strange as it may seem, this really IS one of the funniest movies I've ever seen. Unexpected twists. Bizzare stange things that make no sense. And weird goofy euphemisms. That's what makes me laugh. As another reviewer said, the fist time you see the "anti-theft device" you can't help but laugh. And I really get a kick out of the things Fred says instead of curse words "Sweet swirling onion rings!". And the way he keeps launching into old classic songs (the one from the wizard of OZ was pretty great), it's just not the kind of humor you see in movies very often. But I think this movie's funniest moments come from the over-the-top crazy things that keep happening (the monkey biting his hand and him flailing across the room while other people talk in the next room over oblivous to what's happening, and the testing he goes through in the isolation chamber and the G-Force Tunnel).This movie is good, clean fun and truly appropriate for all ages. If you like any of the movies I mentioned at the outset, or are just looking for something to show the kids, give this one a try.
summary: One of the Funniest Movies I've Ever Seen
